<h2>WebThings IoT Activity Cards </h2>
<span><p>
These <a href="iot.html">WebThings IoT cards</a> show how to connect MicroBlocks
projects to the internet using the free, open-source WebThings Gateway software
running on a Raspberry Pi.
These cards are suitable for grades 6-12, college, and adults.
</p></span>

<h1 id="extended_activities">Extended Activities</h1>
<span><p>
An extended activity is a series of experiments that explore a set of related ideas.
Extended activity guides are written in the form of "teacher notes" but they can also
be used as tutorials. They can be adapted for various grade levels.
</p></span>

<ul class="list">
    <li><a href="cards/tn_Color_Mixing.pdf">Color Mixing</a></li>
    <li><a href="cards/tn_Exploring_Electricity.pdf">Exploring Electricity</a></li>
    <li><a href="cards/tn_micro_bit_dance.pdf">Make a micro:bit Dance</a> (uses old servo blocks)</li>
    <li><a href="cards/tn_Time_Scales.pdf">Time Scales</a></li>
</ul>

<h1 id="remixing">Translating or Remixing Activity Cards and Guides</h1>
<span><p>
Want to translate or remix these materials? They are all available in Google Slides/Docs
format under the Creative Commons CC BY-SA 4.0 license
<a href="https://drive.google.com/open?id=1BxsJ-nEC1MxT67O2bfrHBS9b8nmuMDad">here</a>.
If you translate any materials, please send us a link to your translations
so we can share it with others.
</p></span>

<h2 id="creating">Creating Your Own</h2>
<span><p>
Have ideas for your own activity cards or activity guides?
We encourage you to use the MicroBlocks formats!
However, note that the bunny image, the name "MicroBlocks",
and the phrase "Small, Fast, Human Friendly" are registered US trademarks
and can't be used without written permission from our fiscal sponsor,
the Software Freedom Conservancy.
Those trademarks (including the bunny image) should not appear on your own cards.
<span></p>

<span><p>
If you'd like to share your materials with the MicroBlocks community, please get in touch.
<span></p>

